namespace Pscf {
namespace Rp {

/*! 
\page rp_BdMove_page BdMove

The BdMove classes used by both the pscf_rpc and pscf_rpg programs 
implements a MC move that performs a short BD simulation, and always
accepts the result.

Two closely analogous class templates named Pscf::Rp::BdMove and 
Pscf::Rpg::BdMove are used to perform this type of move in the
pscf_rpc and pscf_rpg programs, respectively. Instantiations of 
these templates are derived from instantiations of the base class 
template Pscf::Rp::BdMove, which defines the implementation of the
move in a generic form.

\see Rp::BdMove (class API)

\section rp_BdMove_algorithm_sec Step Algorithm

To be written (if any)


\section rp_BdMove_parameter_sec Parameter File

The only parameters needed by this algorithm are the "probability" 
parameter, which determines the probability that a move of this type
will be attempted, a required parameter "nStep" that gives the number
of BD steps that should be taken within a single MC move, 
and a required parameter named "mobility", which
is the mobility parameter of the explicit BD step.  A typical example 
of an associated parameter file block is shown below.
\code
  BdMove{
    probability   0.5
    mobility      0.005
    nStep         100
  }
\endcode
The format for this block is thus:
\code
  BdMove{
    probability  float (in range [0,1])
    mobility     float
    nStep        int
  }
\endcode
The meanings of both parameter are summarized briefly below:
<table>
  <tr>
    <td> <b> Label </b>  </td>
    <td> <b> Description </b>  </td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td> probability </td>
    <td> probability of attempting a step of this type  </td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td> mobility </td>
    <td> Mobility parameter of underlying attempted BD step </td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td> nStep </td>
    <td> number of BD steps per MC move of this type </td>
  </tr>
</table>

*/

}
}
